To hit the 120‑day sprint, treat the next 7 days as “infra week” and only set up what unblocks real money: **running Middleman, charging for usage, watching it, and talking to customers**.

***

## Day 1–2: Run Middleman For Real

- Cloud account (compute)
  - Set up: AWS / GCP / Azure / Fly.io (pick one).
  - Purpose: Run the FastAPI Middleman and any background workers.
  - Why now: No live service = no usage, no data, no deals.
  - Build vs buy: Use managed cloud; don’t roll your own hardware.

- Containerization & deployment
  - Set up: Docker + either:
    - Docker Compose on a single VM, or
    - A simple managed container service (ECS/Fargate, Cloud Run, Fly.io apps).
  - Purpose: Build `tap919-middleman` image and deploy `app/main.py` behind a stable URL.
  - Build vs buy: Use Docker and basic managed deploys; don’t hand‑craft VM scripts.

- Database (start with managed Postgres)
  - Set up: Supabase, Neon, RDS, or equivalent Postgres.
  - Purpose: Store Tenants, ApiKeys, PricingRules, UsageEvents, Affiliates.
  - Why now: Without a proper DB, you can’t meter, quote, or analyze.
  - Build vs buy: Use managed Postgres; you can still prototype on SQLite for local dev.

- Secrets management (minimal)
  - Set up: At least `.env` files per environment + cloud secret storage (AWS SSM / Secret Manager, or Doppler if you want).
  - Purpose: Secure DB URL, Stripe keys, provider keys.
  - Build vs buy: Do not build your own vault; just use env variables plus cloud secrets.

***

## Day 2–3: Edge Gateway, Health, And Observability

- Cloudflare account + Workers
  - Set up:
    - Domain or subdomain on Cloudflare.
    - One Worker fronting Middleman with:
      - `/v1/models`
      - `/v1/price`
      - `/v1/execute`
      - `/v1/agent/ping`
  - Purpose: Low‑latency edge API, per‑tenant key headers, affiliate link capture, and routing.
  - Build vs buy: Use Cloudflare Workers; you’re already designing around this.

- Basic monitoring (external)
  - Set up: A simple uptime monitor (Better Uptime, Healthchecks.io, or similar).
  - Purpose:
    - Ping `/internal/ping` on Middleman.
    - Ping Worker `/v1/agent/ping`.
    - Alert via email/Slack on failures.
  - Build vs buy: You can script it later; use a SaaS monitor now.

- Logging / tracing backend (minimal)
  - Set up:
    - Either:
      - Grafana Cloud (Loki + Tempo), or
      - A small self‑hosted Grafana + Tempo/Jaeger stack.
  - Purpose: Receive OpenTelemetry traces from Middleman so you can:
    - See per‑call latency, errors, and cost attribution.
  - Build vs buy: Use existing OTEL stack; don’t invent your own tracing format.

***

## Day 3–4: Billing & Money Flow

- Stripe account & products
  - Set up:
    - Stripe account.
    - At least 2–3 products/prices:
      - A “Tap919 Credits” product for base usage (tokens/requests).
      - A “Tap919 Pro Lane” or “BlackMind Lite” for higher tiers.
  - Purpose: Charge customers for usage and plans.
  - Build vs buy: Use Stripe; building your own card/billing processor is a non‑starter.

- Stripe Billing usage integration (Phase 1)
  - Wire:
    - From `UsageEvent` → Stripe usage records via a background job or agent.
    - At first, even a cron/scheduler that batches daily is fine.
  - Purpose: Convert your usage logs into real bills.
  - Build vs buy: You supply the usage data; Stripe handles invoicing and taxes.

- Basic accounting connection
  - Set up:
    - QuickBooks / Xero at minimum, or at least Stripe → CSV export workflow.
  - Purpose: Keep books clean from day 1 (even if light).
  - Build vs buy: Don’t build an accounting system; just configure exports.

***

## Day 4–5: Front Door, Docs, And Sales Surface

- Marketing / product site
  - Set up:
    - A simple Next.js or static site (Vercel, Cloudflare Pages, or Netlify).
  - Purpose:
    - Explain “Tap919 Agent Gateway.”
    - Highlight usage‑based pricing and “future monopoly prevention.”
    - Provide CTAs for “Get API key” and “Talk to us.”
  - Build vs buy: You’ll build this site; just use a framework and a host, not a homegrown server.

- Documentation hub
  - Set up:
    - GitHub Pages or Docusaurus/GitBook for:
      - API docs (`/v1/*`).
      - Onboarding guides.
      - Runner/affiliate explainer.
  - Purpose: Let agencies and devs self‑serve and test the gateway.
  - Build vs buy: You can roll your own docs later; start with Docusaurus or GitBook.

- Support channel
  - Set up:
    - One central support email (support@) and either:
      - A Slack community, or
      - A simple support SaaS (Help Scout/Zendesk) if you prefer.
  - Purpose: Capture early agency questions and issues in one place.
  - Build vs buy: AetherDesk will eventually absorb this; for week 1, keep it simple.

***

## Day 5–6: Internal Ops & Dev Loop

- Code + CI/CD
  - Set up:
    - GitHub repo (already done).
    - GitHub Actions workflow:
      - Run tests on push.
      - Build Docker image.
      - Deploy to your chosen cloud and optionally update Cloudflare Worker bindings.
  - Purpose: Deploy quickly and safely, iterate daily.
  - Build vs buy: CI from GitHub Actions; don’t build your own pipeline.

- Internal chat & tracking
  - Set up:
    - Slack/Discord workspace.
    - GitHub Issues/Projects for roadmap and bug tracking.
  - Purpose:
    - Track 120‑day sprint tasks.
    - Coordinate content, product, and infra work.
  - Build vs buy: Long term, you can mirror this in AetherDesk; now is not the time.

- Product analytics (optional but powerful)
  - Set up:
    - PostHog or simple event logging in your own DB.
  - Purpose:
    - See which endpoints agents and customers hit.
    - Measure free→paid conversions.
  - Build vs buy: You can later build focused analytics into AetherDesk; use an existing tool or lightweight custom event logging now.

***

## Day 6–7: Runner Affiliate Basics & First Customers

- Runner (affiliate) tracking v1
  - Set up (inside your own stack):
    - `Affiliate` table in Postgres.
    - `affiliate_id` and `affiliate_code` fields.
    - `Tenant.affiliate_id` relationship.
    - Add `?aff=CODE` handling in Cloudflare Worker to attach new tenants to affiliates.
  - Purpose: Make the “instant employee” loop real at a basic level.
  - Build vs buy: This is core IP; build it yourself on Middleman + DB.

- Payout path v1
  - Set up:
    - Decide payout rail: Stripe Connect or PayPal Payouts.
    - Do **manual payouts** for early Runners:
      - Use a query on AffiliatePayout or aggregated UsageEvents to compute owed commissions.
  - Purpose: Show that Runners can really earn and get paid.
  - Build vs buy: You orchestrate the logic & UI; payouts themselves go through Stripe/PayPal.

- First‑agency‑ready flow
  - Ensure:
    - You can:
      - Create a tenant.
      - Issue an API key.
      - Route their calls via Worker → Middleman.
      - See UsageEvents.
      - Generate a simple invoice preview.
    - You can:
      - Attribute usage to an affiliate (Runner) if they came via `?aff=CODE`.
  - Purpose: Be ready to onboard your first paying agency and your first Runner in week 2.

